@Ms. Billie M. Spaight I had excise at first, which fit  perfectly but didn't work out! "Excise" is to remove a portion of a organ. Such as removing a tumor from the lung. "Resect" (which also fits the space and definition) means to remove an entire organ-- a cholecystectomy is a resection of the gallbladder.

Although "ablate" is used for destruction of tissue (such as by burning or abrading it) rather than excision (where you'd have something to send to pathology lab), it's still gone afterwards-- so it HAS been removed. 

One definition of remove in my Webster's is simply "to get rid of", and remove is not a specialist term. Just not removed by cutting, and since the clue didn't specify cutting... it's accurate even by specialist rules. I am a physician.

